<div class="xar-mod-head">
  <span class="xar-mod-title">
    <xar:mlstring>Twitter Administration</xar:mlstring>
  </span>
</div>
<div id="twitter-admin-main" class="xar-mod-body">
  <xar:template type="module" module="twitter" file="user-menu" />
  <img src="#xarTplGetImage('twitter-module-icon3.png','twitter')#" class="xar-module-icon" alt="official icon" width="96" height="96" />

  <h3><xar:mlstring>What is it?</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <p>
    <em><xar:mlstring>Twitter Module provides a wrapper for Twitters API functions.</xar:mlstring></em>
    <xar:mlstring>It is currently responsible for accomplishing these main tasks:</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Provide a means to send status updates to your Twitter account from your site</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Optionally display the Twitter public timeline</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Optionally display a specific user timeline associated with your site.</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Optionally allow users to update their Twitter status from your site.</xar:mlstring></li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Optionally display users Twitter account info in their profiles</xar:mlstring></li>
  </ol>
  <h3><xar:mlstring>How to use it?</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <ul>
        <li>
            <h4><xar:mlstring>Modify Config</xar:mlstring></h4>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring>Module</xar:mlstring>
                    <br />
                    - <xar:mlstring>Configure the modules shorturl and alias options</xar:mlstring>
                    <br />
                    - <xar:mlstring>Configure the tabs to display, and default tab to show for user main function</xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring>Site</xar:mlstring>
                    <br />
                    - <xar:mlstring>Configure the site account and owner</xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring>Users</xar:mlstring>
                    <br />
                    - <xar:mlstring>Configure user profile options</xar:mlstring>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </li>
  </ul>

  <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Blocks</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <ul>
    <li><xar:mlstring>timeline -- Allows you to display public or a user timeline within a block</xar:mlstring></li>
  </ul>

  <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Hooks (TODO)</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <ul>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Create -- Allows a status update to be sent from the site account when new items are created. The hook allows you to send an update for content created by all users, or just items created by the site account owner. Status will include a link to the new item. You can optionally specify a field to include an excerpt from.</xar:mlstring></li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <xar:ml>
        <xar:mlstring>
            In these cases, the Twitter module provides the hook functionality.
            To activate the hooks go to <a href="#(1)">Modules - Configure Hooks - Twitter Module.</a>.
            From there choose the module(s) and/or itemtype(s) you want to activate create hooks for.
            You can then configure settings per module/itemtype from <a href="#(2)">Twitter - Modify Config - Hooks</a>.
        </xar:mlstring>
        <xar:mlvar>#xarModURL('modules','admin','hooks', array('hook' => 'twitter'))#</xar:mlvar>
        <xar:mlvar>#xarModURL('twitter', 'admin', 'modifyconfig', array('tab' => 'hooks'))#</xar:mlvar>
    </xar:ml>
  </p>

  <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Dynamic Data Properties</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <ul>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Twitter provides a twitterscreenname property</xar:mlstring>
    <br />
    - <xar:mlstring>Add a twitterscreenname property to the Roles Users dynamicdata object. Once added your users will be able to enter an account name and password. Their Twitter profile will display in their user account profile, and will also be listed in the Users tab (if you enable it in Module Modify Config).</xar:mlstring>
    </li>

  </ul>

  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>Further Information</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
    <xar:mlstring>Further information on the Twitter module can be found at</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><a title="#xarML('Xaraya Twitter Module')#" href="http://crispcreations.co.uk/xar/mods/twitter"><xar:mlstring>Twitter Module home page</xar:mlstring></a> <xar:mlstring> at CrispCreations</xar:mlstring>
    </li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Twitter Extension page at</xar:mlstring> <a title="#xarML('Twitter Module - Xaraya Extension 991')#" href="http://www.xaraya.com/index.php/release/991.html"><xar:mlstring>Xaraya Extension and Releases</xar:mlstring></a>.
      <xar:mlstring> Click on Version History tab at the bottom to get the latest release information.</xar:mlstring>
    </li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Related tutorials and documentation on Twitter Module found at</xar:mlstring> <a href="http://www.xaraya.com/index.php/keywords/twitter/" title="#xarML('Related documentation on Twitter')#"><xar:mlstring>Xaraya Documentation.</xar:mlstring></a>
    </li>
    <li><xar:mlstring>Twitter Module uses the TwitterAPI, more details of which can be found at the</xar:mlstring> <a href="http://apiwiki.twitter.com/"><xar:mlstring>Twitter API Wiki</xar:mlstring></a>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p class="xar-sub">
    <strong>&nbsp;<xar:mlstring>Twitter Module - Overview</xar:mlstring></strong><br />&nbsp;<xar:mlstring>Version</xar:mlstring> #$version#
  </p>
</div>

